definition.value: A reference substance role that is played by a reference genome when used during sequence alignment.
An algorithm that attempts to align a nucleic acid sequence to a reference genome and transcriptome.
A measurement datum that is the result of the measurement of the number of bases in a DNA or RNA sequence.

label.value: sequencing library input quantity measurement datum

definition.value: A scalar measurement datum that indicates the amount of sequencing library used as input for a sequencer.
A cDNA library that is a collection of short tags from only one end of DNA fragments.
A scalar measurement datum that indicates the amount of specimen collected.
A data item that indicates the dilution of spike-in added to a specimen.

A reference genome transcriptome alignment algorithm that is a standalone RNA-seq alignment algorithm that uses uncompressed suffix arrays and a mapping algorithm similar to those used in large-scale genome alignment tools to align RNA-seq reads to a genomic reference.
A sequencing assay that incorporates single-end reads and sequencing technology to determine transcripts, gene structures, and gene expressions.

An alignment counting algorithm that assigns gene features to genomic alignments using a hierarchical assignment scheme, which allows simultaneous quantification of multiple feature types or annotation levels without repeatedly assigning reads.
A material separation device also commerically known as Isoraft, that is used to isolate single cells.
A device that is a laboratory tool commonly used in chemistry, biology and medicine to transport a measured volume of liquid, often as a media dispenser.

A material entity that is an individual living system, such as animal, plant, bacteria or virus, that is capable of replicating or reproducing, growth and maintenance in the right environment. An organism may be unicellular or made up, like humans, of many billions of cells divided into specialized tissues and organs.
A material entity that has the specimen role.
A flow_cytometer_sorter is a flow_cytometer that analyzes and separates or sorts particles passing through (based on properties measured during analysis) to collect cells of interest.
A DNA sequencer is an instrument that determines the order of deoxynucleotides in deoxyribonucleic acid sequences.
the use of a chemical or biochemical means to infer the sequence of a biomaterial
the use of enzymes to increase the number of molecules of a biomaterial
An algorithm that attempts to align two molecular sequences (nucleic acid or protein sequences).

BLAST (Basic Local Alignment Search Tool), a pairwise sequence alignment algorithm is a heuristic search algorithm for comparing primary biological sequence information, such as the amino-acid or nucleotides sequences with a database of sequences, and identify sequences that resemble the query sequence above a certain threshold.
A data format specification for molecular sequence feature information.
A BLAST algorithm that searches/aligns a nucleotide query sequence against a nucleotide database at a nucleotide level.
A sequence data that is about the primary structure of RNA.
A processual entity whose completion is hypothesized (by a healthcare provider) to alleviate the signs and symptoms associated with a disorder
The principle investigtor or responsible person for a study or a sample collection.
A data item that indicates the time when the collection of a specimen occurred.

label.value: Illumina TruSeq Rapid SBS Kit v2

definition.value: A collection of sequences (often chromosomes) taken as the standard for a given organism and genome assembly.
A level of depth of a taxon in a taxonomic hierarchy.
Anatomical entity that has mass.
A role played by a a biological sample in the context of an experiment where the intent is that biological or technical variation is measured.
FASTQ format is a text-based format for storing both a biological sequence (usually nucleotide sequence) and its corresponding quality scores.
BAM is the compressed binary version of the Sequence Alignment/Map (SAM) format
